<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> The Burden Is Too Much For One Hobbit To Carry<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(3.82)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1625'>Derek "UnknownGlyph" Tessier</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1625&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 17, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> A Burden To Large<br>
<br>
As one reads the Lord Of The Rings novels, you may notice that many times over the course of Frodo&#8217;s journey the &#8220;one ring&#8221; gets heavier and heavier.  He feels that he can&#8217;t even carry it anymore.  This concept has been grasped by the &#8220;higher beings&#8221; at decipher with the aspect of burdens.  When you read the rules to this game the easiest victory seems to be in direct battling of the fellowship.  Well I agree a deck cannot exist with out fighting it out with the fellowship, but why not burden Frodo and end the game that way.  The tools are there they only need to recognized and used.<br>
<br>
The influence of Saruman on the journey to destroy the ring is apparent in the books and the movies.  His influence is further seen the power Isengard has on the corruption of the ring bearer.<br>
Cruel Caradhas - Exert an Isengard minion to exert the ring bearer or add a burden.  Seems simple enough, most players in early game will just toss on the burden rather than have Frodo come closer to death.  Using this card after other attempts to raise the burden number may only result in Frodo taking a wound so timing the use of this card is essential to its success.<br>
Saruman&#8217;s Reach - Exert an Uruk-hai to have opponent exert 2 companions or have ring bearer wear the &#8220;one ring&#8221; thereby adding burdens.  The bonuses of this card are two-fold, you either have weaker companions to battle in combat or the ring bearer has just added at least one burden.  Also once the ring bearer is wearing the ring many more cards can be used to enhance battle.<br>
Uruk Spy - If Ring-bearer puts on the &#8220;one ring&#8221; exert the spy, discard a card from top of your draw deck for each Isengard minion, add a burden for each shadow card discarded this way.  Um wow in conjunction with Saruman&#8217;s Reach you now start loading up on the burdens.<br>
Worry - Each time an Uruk-hai wins a skirmish ring-bearer must exert or add a burden.  In conjunction with Cruel Caradhas you&#8217;ll see Frodo either takes a bunch of wounds or start stacking up the &#8220;weight&#8221; of the one ring.<br>
<br>
As this shows, Saruman and his minions truly do work for the One Eye forcing the tiny hobbit to slowly be overcome by the great evil of the one ring.  Play the cards right and you could see your opponent looking at a fellowship of eight companions staring down at an evil Frodo Baggins.<br>
<br>
Moria has less potential of enhance the effect of burdens upon Frodo but they can cause some damage.<br>
Goblin Spear - Arm a moria minion and if that minion kills a companion in a skirmish add a burden, two if a hobbit was slain.  This card has potential but requires some massive but kicking by moria minions, still against a deck of all hobbits the potential for quickly adding burdens is there.<br>
Lost To The Goblins - If ring-bearer takes a wound or exerts spot a moria minion, for each minion spotted discard a card, add a burden for each shadow card discarded up to 3 burdens.  Well now this seems similar to Uruk spy except this is an event.  Seems like it could be quite successful since you could toss out a lot of moria minions for very little twilight.<br>
<br>
Although Moria has limited involvement in piling on the corruption it could be a good idea to combine this with another culture.<br>
<br>
Ringwraiths were present from the beginning of the movie to the end.  These powerful minions wreck havoc on the field and can deal some nasty damage off the field.<br>
Blade Tip - If Nazgul wins a skirmish play on defeated companion, that companion then gets wounded each round, if it&#8217;s the ring-bearer he gets burdens instead.  Works great if you can goad Frodo into fighting otherwise it&#8217;s of limited use to directly affecting the burdens.<br>
Drawn To Its Power - Each time a Nazgul kills a companion add a burden.  Seems effective enough, kill off some companions and stack on the evil counters.  Only problem is killing of those pesky companions.  Some tweaking to a battling deck only splashing burden adders would give the best result but then you aren&#8217;t focussed on corrupting Frodo.<br>
In The Ringwraith&#8217;s Wake - If a Nazgul wins a skirmish exert the ring-bearer or add a burden.  Ah this seems much more likely and gives a much better chance to adding burdens to Frodo since you could have many skirmishes per turn, your chances of winning one of them is that much greater.<br>
The Twilight World - If the ring-bearer puts on the ring, exert a Nazgul to add 2 burdens.  Oh nice, combine this with Saruman&#8217;s Reach and you have a nice combo which adds up to 4 burdens.<br>
<br>
Ringwraiths have a decent attack against Frodo, which only makes sense, they do work directly for the One Eye.  Have the ringwraiths and isengard work together and you&#8217;ll soon see Frodo fighting alongside them, racing to give the ring to the one eye.<br>
<br>
Finally Sauron, this culture has the most cards that play around with corrupting Frodo<br>
Despair - If the total number of burdens and dead companions is 12 or greater exert a sauron orc and Frodo is corrupted.  Well ok, after you add up some burdens and stomp on a few companions Frodo is destined to lose faith.  Although 12 is a hard number to reach it is possible so packing one of these in your deck would be enough to have it available for use.<br>
Desperate Defense Of The Ring - Play to a companion, each time that companion is assigned to skirmish opponent discards 3 cards from their hand or adds a burden to ring-bearer.  Sounds good enough, either they start depleting their deck or just add a simple burden to Frodo.  Should make him easier to corrupt for you.<br>
The Irresistible Shadow - If you can spot 5 burdens and free peoples have no cards in draw deck ring-bearer is corrupted.  Hmm this could quite possibly work well with D.D.O.T.R. making them cycle through their deck so Frodo gets corrupted with only a few burdens, possibly the number he started with from the bidding.<br>
The Ring&#8217;s Oppression - If a Sauron orc kills a companion add a burden, 3 if the ring-bearer wears the ring.  Ah use this with Saruman&#8217;s Reach and all of a sudden you are &#8531; closer to corrupting the hobbit.<br>
Thin And Stretched - Exert sauron orc play to ring-bearer.  Add a burden if he doesn&#8217;t skirmish if another companion did.  Well here&#8217;s the way you get Frodo to fight against the Nazgul.  And if he doesn&#8217;t want to fight he takes a burden.<br>
<br>
Sauron enables you to tackle Frodo from many angles and have the free people making very difficult decisions, lose some cards, let Frodo fight (possibly getting overwhelmed), or just add a burden.<br>
<br>
After looking at the potential of the Shadow to corrupt Frodo it&#8217;s a wonder the poor hobbit hasn&#8217;t become a follower of the one eye.  Now you&#8217;re probably going to say &#8220;well that&#8217;s all great and that but there&#8217;s that pesky Sam, Son of Hamfest&#8221; this is very true and going through the cards I&#8217;ve found some ways to reduce his effectiveness or eliminate him completely.  Of course some of the combos are quite card intensive but so far there is only one set to draw from.<br>
<br>
Frenzy - If the good people of middle earth decide to exhaust Sam to remove 3 points of their bid just toss out this card.  Forces them to assign an exhausted companion to fight one of your Moria minions.  Good enough, Sam&#8217;s not that tough and all you need to do is one damage now.  Seems to work quite well.<br>
Toldea, Dark Whispers, Black Breath & Nazgul Sword - Spot 4 burdens, then force Sam to fight this huge Nazgul, equipped with a Nazgul sword, add a dark whispers and this nasty is doing 3 damage if he wins the skirmish.  Toss in a black breath to prevent any healing by Sam, along with any blade tips and your deck Sam is as good as dead if he wasn&#8217;t already.  Of course you don&#8217;t need all these cards to injure Sam but with all of them your chances of eliminating Frodo&#8217;s buddy in one shot are much easier.<br>
Enquea - Hmm spot 5 burdens, exert Enquea and toss a wound on a companion, again if Sam&#8217;s exhausted from removing burdens, um he&#8217;s dead or if you just battle Sam with Toldea this is again a quick kill.  Quite a nasty combo.<br>
Morgul Skirmisher - Exert this little guy to exert a hobbit.  Oh wait isn&#8217;t Sam a hobbit, hehe there goes Sam again getting forced to take one for the team.<br>
<br>
Of course there are probably many other ways to eliminate the possible threat of a Samwise Gamgee take over but this few preventatives will easily fit into a burden deck without reducing your burden adding effectiveness.<br>
<br>
Throughout this whole splurge of text you&#8217;ve seen the many ways to add burdens, once they&#8217;re on the ring-bearer many new cards that add strength, damage and other things to minions can then be played.  I leave that to you to develop and test out.  Remember corrupting Frodo isn&#8217;t that popular an idea so you may just catch your opponent asleep at the wheel and spell their doom.  Leaving Aragorn and Legolas with full quivers, Gandalf and Boromir with a clean swords and the short dwarves and hobbits yearning to show that size doesn&#8217;t always matter.  But all for not because their unlikely hero is possessed by the &#8220;one ring&#8221;<br>
<br>
Catch-Ya-Later<br>
